03:25.691 --> 03:26.693
He came out all right. He was only gone five days, 
but I was in Los Angeles and it was just, two months

03:33.398 --> 03:36.122
before my son was born. So I didn't meet any of these 
newspaper men. My father was an old newspaper man

03:42.391 --> 03:48.781
and he met them out on the porch of our home there in 
Los Angeles. My parents lived in Los Angeles. Of

03:54.070 --> 03:59.058
course, he was trying to fend off the reporters, 
and I wouldn't see them. So all of these things that

03:59.559 --> 04:07.551
were in these press notices were very disturbing 
to me because they were garbled, you know. And

04:08.353 --> 04:11.998
every time a newspaper would come out, I'd just go 
into hysterics. Well, when did you first hear that

04:12.840 --> 04:15.624
he'd been kidnapped? Well, I had... He was a 
very... almost providential thing because I took

04:20.598 --> 04:43.960
my daughter who was then four and went on the 
streetcar which was at 5th and 6th

04:20.598 --> 04:43.960
and Coronado and went down to the corner of 7th and 
Broadway on the streetcar. I was just getting out

04:43.980 --> 04:48.765
of home because I had had the flu the week before and 
I wanted to get out. And I heard these people

04:49.032 --> 04:56.603
calling the extras on the other two corners 
across. But I got off on this corner and walked

04:57.124 --> 05:03.434
directly across the street to get my bus back home. 
And they were calling all about the American

05:04.074 --> 05:07.800
kidnapped in Mexico. And it didn't down on me that 
it was my husband because they'd had so much

05:07.780 --> 05:16.492
trouble down around Fresnillo and the mines down 
there. And I just thought it was, just because it

05:17.073 --> 05:20.899
was Mexico, it was disturbing. And I got home and my 
father was out on the back porch just nervously

05:21.620 --> 05:28.770
looking at these newspapers. And I said, well, 
Dad, you might as well bring the papers in. I know

05:32.034 --> 05:34.598
about it already. Then I looked at the headlines 
and I said, well I didn't know it was my husband. And

05:40.587 --> 05:51.624
then of course I called the telegraph office, 
Western Union, and they said that they had had a

05:40.587 --> 05:51.624
consular message for me and they'd been trying to 
locate me. This was on a Monday. They'd been trying

05:53.106 --> 05:58.695
to locate me since

05:59.857 --> 06:00.478
Saturday. This didn't happen on Friday night. And 
because I was visiting my parents, who were named

06:03.021 --> 06:14.216
Adams, you see, they had, they had, they were named 
Kemp, and they were canvassing all the Adams in the

06:03.021 --> 06:14.216
directory. And so, of course, as soon as I 
identified myself, I got the message from the

06:22.030 --> 06:25.460
consulate in Saltia and from the mining company. 
It was the American Metals Company in New York. And

06:28.689 --> 06:32.219
I got my messages from them. They assured me that 
that was in here the They assured me that he was.

06:39.702 --> 06:40.603
This is the message. Your husband, held for ransom 
by Mexican rebels, have just received word he is

06:40.623 --> 06:47.655
being well treated. This office and the company 
doing everything possible to procure his

06:48.216 --> 06:52.222
release. And this was February 16, 1920. So this 
was actually rather late in the revolutionary

06:55.988 --> 06:59.854
period. Well, it was an interesting experience. 
He came out all right. There's never a time when

07:03.340 --> 07:08.387
it's very convenient to have a thing like that 
happen. Not exactly. No, I shouldn't think so.

