did you all, until the bandits came, did you feel

15:11.264 --> 15:26.843
terribly threatened by any of the things that were 
going on, or did he, or did they pretty much leave

15:11.264 --> 15:26.843
him alone?

15:28.763 --> 15:33.147
You always had a, when you're young, you know, 
those things don't affect you very much. I guess we

15:33.267 --> 15:54.787
really felt a little uneasy all the time, because 
when I first went down there and Betty was a baby, I

15:33.267 --> 15:54.787
kept a little satchel packed with her baby food and 
her bottle and her diapers and all, so that if we had

15:33.267 --> 15:54.787
to get out on short notice, we could leave. And one 
night, this, we were, We had been told that the

15:59.510 --> 16:05.864
bandits were roving around the station, which was 
two miles down from the camp. And so we went to bed

16:06.986 --> 16:09.011
rather uneasy. And then there was a, we kept a 
watchman outside the house all night long. They

16:16.098 --> 16:33.837
had a system of alarms all over the camp, so that if 
there was a bandit alarm, he would ring on an old

16:16.098 --> 16:33.837
rail in the backyard, you know, soundless alarm, 
and the watchmen at the different levels over the

16:16.098 --> 16:33.837
mine would answer it, so that the whole camp would 
be alarmed. And in the middle of the night, he came

16:33.817 --> 16:39.886
to our window and he said, here they come, I'm in. 
And Mr. Adams asked, how many? And he said there

16:43.612 --> 16:47.557
were five bandits and they were on the trail back to 
our house. So Mr. Adams said, well, sound the

16:48.158 --> 16:50.221
alarm. So we heard him go back and sound this alarm. 
And we got into our clothes as quickly as we could,

16:54.067 --> 17:04.902
and I wrapped the baby in a blanket and got all ready 
to go down to the mine. And Mr. Adams took me down to

17:04.942 --> 17:10.649
the entrance of the mine. There was a little 
railroad that went into the entrance of the mine.

17:14.114 --> 17:24.480
And he left me there with the assistant 
superintendent, and he went back up the trail to

17:14.114 --> 17:24.480
wait for the bandits. And the three burros came 
down the trail.

17:36.085 --> 17:42.614
So

17:36.085 --> 17:42.614
it was much less threatening than it had appeared. 
We went through all the thrills, as it were.

17:48.743 --> 17:57.175
So we had a number of...

17:48.743 --> 17:57.175
What about the common people, the miners and 
people like that? Did they talk very much about

17:57.335 --> 18:02.683
what was going on, or were they very much afraid? 
Well, no, they were not. They were a very ignorant

18:04.841 --> 18:15.353
class, and all

18:04.841 --> 18:15.353
they wanted was a livelihood. They wanted the mine 
to continue and get their money. And of course, if

18:22.582 --> 18:25.465
they didn't

18:27.436 --> 18:35.325
That was their only means of support because there 
wasn't much agricultural pursuits around there.

18:35.346 --> 18:53.147
They had small ranches, but they were owned, you 
see, the ranches were owned by the money-class

18:35.346 --> 18:53.147
people, and these workmen could only get day's 
wages wherever they worked, you know. They didn't

18:53.167 --> 18:57.392
have much, much prospect of substantial living.

19:03.088 --> 19:08.076
And of course they, most of them, mining was all 
they knew. This was a lead and zinc and some silver

19:09.038 --> 19:15.668
mine. And they had, they brought it out on little, 
of course they had stoats in the mine where they

19:16.369 --> 19:26.164
knocked the ore down into these little carts. and 
they ran it out to the entrance of the mine in the

19:26.448 --> 19:47.190
carts, and then they loaded it onto a tramway, 
which was a system of trestles and buckets that ran

19:26.448 --> 19:47.190
down the mountainside, you see, and they The 
filled buckets, the weight of the filled buckets

19:48.824 --> 19:59.422
taking the ore down was sufficient to bring the 
empties back up, you see, on this tramway, they

19:48.824 --> 19:59.422
called it. That was interesting. I think that 
tramway is still there. You go on the railroad to,

20:04.531 --> 20:12.505
between Monterey and Saltillo, it's about 
halfway between Monterey and Saltillo. But

20:12.525 --> 20:13.887
the... The Mexican government has taken over all 
those mines now. They're government controlled.

20:20.576 --> 20:24.119
And I don't think that mine was good enough. It was 
rich enough that they probably aren't mining it at

20:24.859 --> 20:28.643
all now. But during the war days, you see this was 
during the war days that we were down there. And we

20:37.951 --> 20:44.076
had to get all our supplies through the American 
consulate in Monterey. I remember when we wanted,

20:44.647 --> 20:58.980
Betty had the lupine cough and we wanted, I wanted 
special food for her because she didn't seem to be

20:44.647 --> 20:58.980
able to take the food that we were giving her. I 
remember I was paying a dollar, a dollar and a half

21:00.282 --> 21:11.312
for a little can of the more than sweetened milk, 
you know. Condensed milk? Condensed milk, yes.

21:19.000 --> 21:23.929
But not the, it's the sweetened kind, you know. 
That seemed to be all sweetened. At one stage, we

21:26.734 --> 21:34.448
had a goat, and we gave her goat's milk, and they The 
Mexican people that you met down there were very

21:35.170 --> 21:52.232
friendly, and I remember this woman who lived over 
at the ranch that sent our vegetables in from the

21:35.170 --> 21:52.232
Jewish, and she had sent us milk, but we didn't have 
to boil it. Of course, it didn't do very well, but

21:52.252 --> 22:03.827
she said that the child should have goat's milk and 
have it warm right from the goat, And so the Mexican

22:03.976 --> 22:20.837
mozo, he'd come in and I'd have him scrub his hands 
in the kitchen, wash them very clean, and give him a

22:03.976 --> 22:20.837
little cup with a linen cloth to strain it through. 
And he would go up on the hillside and he'd milk the

22:20.897 --> 22:28.667
goat and strain it right into her cup and she'd 
drink it. Well, that was the thing that this

22:29.002 --> 22:35.493
Mexican woman told me. How did it work? It worked. 
It worked very well. Because we'd been having to

22:38.799 --> 22:52.242
send the secretary, a boy from his office by train 
down to Saltillo to bring the milk back, you see. So

22:53.352 --> 22:55.680
this didn't work very well. But we had a number of 
very primitive experiences down there. It seems

23:02.093 --> 23:06.719
so long ago, I haven't talked about it for so long, 
it's hard to remember. Do you remember

23:09.142 --> 23:14.468
approximately what the miners made each day for 
their labor? I just don't know what the prices

23:15.209 --> 23:19.915
were. Of course, they were paid in Mexican 
currency.

23:25.062 --> 23:26.143
Right.

23:28.418 --> 23:32.108
I think the ratio was two to one at that time. Of 
course, that has changed a good many times, you

23:32.990 --> 23:37.943
know. Then at one time, when Mr. Adams was 
kidnapped by these bandits up above Saltea, He

23:46.036 --> 23:47.578
wasn't paying them. He was paying them in script, 
which they'd have to take down into the city to get

23:47.598 --> 24:01.152
cashed, because he didn't dare keep money at the 
mine. And that was the reason, really, they took

24:01.853 --> 24:09.101
him out when they kidnapped him, was because they 
asked for money, and he said he didn't have any

24:01.853 --> 24:09.101
money. And because he was paying in script, And so 
they said, well, we'll have to take you with us

24:14.318 --> 24:18.703
until we get our money back. And that's how they did 
it. Was this a regular point? Did the bandits do

24:26.291 --> 24:28.333
this regularly? Was it something to be expected? I 
mean, were the bandits kidnapping people for

24:31.537 --> 24:37.343
money during this period? Well, this happened. 
There had been a good many kidnappings about that

24:39.749 --> 25:04.896
time, and I think one of these clippings in here 
tells about how Villa had said that he was going to

24:39.749 --> 25:04.896
capture 12 Americans, and until he got his money 
back, Villa claimed that he had sent his

25:06.597 --> 25:25.055
representative up with money to buy supplies, and 
the man had absconded with the money, and he said

25:06.597 --> 25:25.055
that until he got his money back, he was going to 
kidnap Americans and hold them until he was

25:06.597 --> 25:25.055
reimbursed. Now, this was actually after 
Pershing had left Mexico, wasn't it? Yes. Yes. So V

25:36.857 --> 25:40.021
was still actively... But you say these men did not 
claim to be V. Eustace. Well, the men that...

25:53.659 --> 25:58.705
The men that took him out claimed to be V. Eustace. 
They were all... I think there were about 12 men,

26:00.748 --> 26:04.853
and they all seemed to have... colonel status. 
Twelve colonels? My goodness. They were all

26:08.261 --> 26:09.642
colonels. And one of them even was a mason. This was 
very queer. Was

26:14.949 --> 26:23.599
your husband a mason too? No. Well, no. His father 
had been a mason. Mr. Adams went to Mexico as a young

26:27.123 --> 26:34.232
high engineer right out of college and never had 
taken up, he really never had settled himself any

26:35.545 --> 26:40.977
place to be affiliated. His father had been a 
nation. The men that held him, were they Did he

26:48.303 --> 26:51.128
describe them as being fairly well educated? They 
were all fairly well educated. They were not the

26:53.894 --> 26:59.244
class of men that he'd been working with in the mine 
at all. And he said that as they

27:00.265 --> 27:09.062
gave him a horse to ride,

27:10.173 --> 27:16.583
He said as they rode, they could see the Federal 
troops in the distance, but they never caught up

27:10.173 --> 27:16.583
with them. He said they didn't try. The Federal 
troops were supposed to be out trying to locate

27:18.626 --> 27:24.896
them, you see. And he said they could see them as 
they were driving, riding along, and they would

27:24.916 --> 27:36.113
camp at the different, well I guess common, just 
commandeered Any ramps they came to, they would

27:36.498 --> 27:43.977
just require them to feed them and feed their 
horses. But they rode over the hills for five days.

27:59.178 --> 28:01.441
Did he ever hear from any of these men later? Did he 
ever find out what happened to them? No. The man who

28:04.885 --> 28:25.350
came to rescue him was, had been at one time, his 
name was Gutierrez, and he had been one of those

28:04.885 --> 28:25.350
interim presidents, well, president probably 
for a day or a very short period at one time in

28:04.885 --> 28:25.350
Mexico. And when he came, he came out to to rescue 
the saddles. And he simply gave his word to the

28:32.619 --> 28:40.569
bandits that he would bring them their army. So he 
acted as a go-between. And they released your

28:44.774 --> 28:49.360
husband before they had the money? Yes. But this 
man Gutierrez, of course, we've always thought

28:51.422 --> 28:57.670
that he was in on them. because he merely gave them 
his word that the money would be paid to them. And I

