35:55.281 --> 36:11.577
that he sort of pinched him and told him when he had 
his Spanish.

36:12.130 --> 36:13.291
Oh, excuse me. It was a very interesting life for 
them. I'm curious, did you ever hear from

36:16.114 --> 36:19.918
Gutierrez again? Did your husband ever hear from 
any of these people that had kidnapped him later

36:19.938 --> 36:24.402
on? Or hear what happened to him? No, I don't think 
he ever did.

36:35.033 --> 36:37.716
I never thought about that. I think perhaps they 
just melted into the, they took their money and

36:38.084 --> 36:43.094
ran. Because that was all, that was all they 
wanted. There was nothing, it wasn't anything

36:46.962 --> 36:49.628
personal. They had no... a particular claim 
against him, they just wanted their money, and he

36:52.073 --> 37:07.211
said in this write-up in his book, he said they 
apologized any number of times for taking him out

36:52.073 --> 37:07.211
if they did. They were very, very polite and very 
solicitous for his comfort. Of course, they said

37:12.517 --> 37:15.921
they had to have their money. They knew they would 
get it. They knew that the mining company would pay

37:17.655 --> 37:21.300
it because they paid it for other men. They had 
taken other men out. I think the superintendent of

37:24.185 --> 37:34.801
the smelter had been taken out to the health events 
and the mining company had paid it. So it wasn't an

37:34.821 --> 37:40.269
uncommon experience. Was anyone ever killed? by 
this particular group of men? No, I don't think so.

37:45.963 --> 37:49.995
They were not violent men. They just needed money 
for the revolution, like I said.

